 inconsistencies, such as prolonged audio-visual desynchronization, span much longer durations and primarily manifest in low and mid-frequency temporal patterns. A standard Mamba block scans the sequence step-by-step (stride 1). While this captures all temporal details, it is computationally redu", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "3becb783-1d57-4f2f-807d-c781f6aeba7b", "uuid": "c71dac17-cbab-4f92-bffe-442153bc45c2", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T05:22:18.535Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "ter inference and superior robustness. II related work II-A Temporal Forgery Localization Early multimedia forensics approaches [ 13 , 21 , 33 , 35 , 36 ] focused primarily on binary classification, often failing to provide precise temporal boundaries. To address this, architectures from Temporal Action Localization (TAL), such as ActionFormer [ 32 ] and TriDet [ 26 ] , were repurposed as strong baselines. Subsequently, dedicated TFL frameworks emerged to tackle specific forgery challenges: UMMAFormer [ 34 ] integrates temporal abnormality attention; DiMoDif [ 20 ] leverages cross-modal differentiation to capture lip-speech inconsistencies; and UniCaCLF [ 31 ] employs context-aware contrastive learning. However, these SOTA methods predominantly rely on Transformer backbones. Despite their effectiveness, they suffer from quadratic computational complexity O ​ ( T 2 ) O(T^{2}) , creating significant efficiency bottlenecks for long video sequences. II-B State Space Models State Space Models (SSMs) have evolved from early structured variants (e.g., S4 [ 18 ] , H3 [ 14 ] , Gated State Space [ 24 ] ) to the recent Mamba [ 17 ] and Mamba2 [ 12 ] , which achieve Transformer-level performance with linear complexity O ​ ( T ) O(T) via selective scanning. In the visual domain, architectures such as ViM [ 37 ] , VMamba [ 22 ] , and Video Mamba Suite [ 10 ] have successfully adapted bidirectional scanning for image and video analysis, while MambaTAD [ 23 ] explored