for precise boundary regression. Bidirectional Mamba Backbone. To efficiently model long-range dependencies, we leverage the Mamba architecture [ 17 ] , specifically the Decomposed Bidirectional Mamba (DBM) block [ 10 ] . Unlike Transformers with 𝒪 ​ ( T 2 ) \\mathcal{O}(T^{2}) complexity, Mamba employs a selective scan mechanism with linear complexity 𝒪 ​ ( T ) \\mathcal{O}(T) . It discretizes the continuous state space equation 𝐡 ′ ​ ( t ) = 𝐀𝐡 ​ ( t ) + 𝐁 ​ x ​ ( t ) \\mathbf{h}^{\\prime}(t)=\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{h}(t)+\\mathbf{B}x(t) into a recurrent form 𝐡 k = 𝐀 ¯ ​ 𝐡 k − 1 + 𝐁 ¯ ​ x k \\mathbf{h}_{k}=\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}\\mathbf{h}_{k-1}+\\bar{\\mathbf{B}}x_{k} , where system matrices are input-dependent. To capture non-causal context essential for TFL, the DBM block processes sequences in both forward and backward directions, fusing the outputs to incorporate comprehensive temporal context. This serves as the fundamental building unit of our UniSkip-Mamba. III-B Unified Multi-Modal Fusion To effectively model the cross-modal inconsistencies inherent in audio-visual forgeries, a principled fusion strategy is essential. As shown in the Unified Sequence Generation Module of Fig. 2 , we transform the separate audio and visual streams into a single, modality-aware sequence. First, assuming both modalities are synchronized to a sequence length T T , we align the visual features 𝐅 v ∈ ℝ B × C v × T \\mathbf{F}_{v}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times C_{v}\\times T} to the audio feature dimension C a C_{a} using a linear projection layer: 𝐅 v ′ = Linear C v → C a ​ ( 𝐅 v ) ∈ ℝ B × C a × T . \\mathbf{F}_{v}^{\\prime}=\\text{Linear}_{C_{v}\\rightarrow C_{a}}(\\mathbf{F}_{v})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times C_{a}\\times T}. (1) Then, instead of channel-wise concatenation, we concatenate the aligned features along the temporal dimension to construct a unified sequence: 𝐅 unified = Concat temporal ​ ( 𝐅 v ′ , 𝐅 a ) ∈ ℝ B × C a × 2 ​ T . \\mathbf{F}_{\\text{unified}}=\\text{Concat}_{\\text{temporal}}(\\mathbf{F}_{v}^{\\prime},\\mathbf{F}_{a})\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times C_{a}\\times 2T}. (2) Finally, to explicitly inform the model of each token’s origin, learnable modality embeddings are introduced. A modality ID sequence is created and passed through an embedding layer to generate the modality vectors 𝐄 modal ∈ ℝ B × 2 ​ T × C a \\mathbf{E}_{\\text{modal}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times 2T\\times C_{a}} , which are then added element-wise to the unified sequence. The final modality-aware sequence 𝐅 input \\mathbf{F}_{\\text{input}} , which serves as the input to our backbone, is formulated as: 𝐅 input = Permute ​ ( 𝐅 unified ) + 𝐄 modal ∈ ℝ B × 2 ​ T × C a , \\mathbf{F}_{\\text{input}}=\\text{Permute}(\\mathbf{F}_{\\text{unified}})+\\mathbf{E}_{\\text{modal}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times 2T\\times C_{a}}, (3) where Permute ​ ( ⋅ ) \\text{Permute}(\\cdot) transposes the last two dimensions to match the input requirements of the backbone. This fusion method offers two key advantages. First, creating a single temporal sequence is naturally aligned with the architecture of our Mamba backbone, facilitating effective cross-modal temporal modeling. Second, the explicit modality embeddings provide a strong, differentiable prior, allowing the model to more efficiently learn forgery patterns instead of discovering modality information implicitly. Algorithm 1 Efficient Skip-Scanning Mamba (S-Mamba) Block 1: Input sequence 𝐗 i ​ n ∈ ℝ B × L × C \\mathbf{X}_{in}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times L\\times C} (where L = 2 ​ T L=2T for the first layer), Skip step p p , Bidirectional Mamba DBM ​ ( ⋅ ) \\text{DBM}(\\cdot) 2: Output sequence 𝐗 o ​ u ​ t ∈ ℝ B × L × C \\mathbf{X}_{out}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{B\\times L\\times C} 3: function Grouping ( 𝐗 , p \\mathbf{X},p ) 4: B , L , C ← 𝐗 . shape B,L,C\\leftarrow\\mathbf{X}.\\text{shape} 5: 𝐗 ← Reshape ​ ( 𝐗 , ( B , L / p , p , C ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Reshape}(\\mathbf{X},(B,L/p,p,C)) ⊳ \\triangleright Split sequence into p p interleaved groups 6: 𝐗 ← Permute ​ ( 𝐗 , ( 0 , 2 , 1 , 3 ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Permute}(\\mathbf{X},(0,2,1,3)) ⊳ \\triangleright To ( B , p , L / p , C ) (B,p,L/p,C) 7: 𝐗 ← Reshape ​ ( 𝐗 , ( B ⋅ p , L / p , C ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Reshape}(\\mathbf{X},(B\\cdot p,L/p,C)) ⊳ \\triangleright Stack groups into batch dim 8: return 𝐗 \\mathbf{X} 9: end function 10: 11: function Merging ( 𝐗 , B , L , C , p \\mathbf{X},B,L,C,p ) 12: 𝐗 ← Reshape ​ ( 𝐗 , ( B , p , L / p , C ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Reshape}(\\mathbf{X},(B,p,L/p,C)) 13: 𝐗 ← Permute ​ ( 𝐗 , ( 0 , 2 , 1 , 3 ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Permute}(\\mathbf{X},(0,2,1,3)) ⊳ \\triangleright To ( B , L / p , p , C ) (B,L/p,p,C) 14: 𝐗 ← Reshape ​ ( 𝐗 , ( B , L , C ) ) \\mathbf{X}\\leftarrow\\text{Reshape}(\\mathbf{X},(B,L,C)) ⊳ \\triangleright Restore original unified sequence 15: return 𝐗 \\mathbf{X} 16: end function 17: 18: 𝐗 n ​ o ​ r ​ m ← LayerNorm ​ ( 𝐗 i ​ n ) \\mathbf{X}_{norm}\\leftarrow\\text{LayerNorm}(\\mathbf{X}_{in}) 19: 𝐗 g ​ r ​ o ​ u ​ p ​ e ​ d ← Grouping ( 𝐗 n ​ o ​ r ​ m , p ) \\mathbf{X}_{grouped}\\leftarrow\\text{{Grouping}($\\mathbf{X}_{norm},p$)} ⊳ \\triangleright Reduce effective length for efficiency 20: 𝐗 s ​ c ​ a ​ n ​ n ​ e ​ d ← DBM ​ ( 𝐗 g ​ r ​ o ​ u ​ p ​ e ​ d ) \\mathbf{X}_{scanned}\\leftarrow\\text{DBM}(\\mathbf{X}_{grouped}) ⊳ \\triangleright Process sub-sequences in parallel 21: 𝐗 m ​ e ​ r ​ g ​ e ​ d ← Merging ( 𝐗 s ​ c ​ a ​ n ​ n ​ e ​ d , B , L , C , p ) \\mathbf{X}_{merged}\\leftarrow\\text{{Merging}($\\mathbf{X}_{scanned},B,L,C,p$)} 22: 𝐗 o ​ u ​ t ← 𝐗 i ​ n + Dropout ​ ( 𝐗 m ​ e ​ r ​ g ​ e ​ d ) \\mathbf{X}_{out}\\leftarrow\\mathbf{X}_{in}+\\text{Dropout}(\\mathbf{X}_{merged}) ⊳ \\triangleright Residual connection 23: return 𝐗 o ​ u ​ t \\mathbf{X}_{out} III-C Efficient Skip-Scanning Mamba Block Figure 3: Illustration of our proposed Efficient Skip-Scanning Mamba (S-Mamba) Block. It introduces a “Group-Scan-Merge” mechanism: splitting the input sequence into p p groups to enable efficient parallel scanning with reduced sequence lengths, effectively acting as a temporal regularizer. Motivation: The Granularity–Efficiency Trade-off. Temporal forgery artifacts exhibit significant diversity in duration and scale. Micro-level artifacts require dense temporal sampling to capture subtle frame-level inconsistencies, whereas macro-level inconsistencies, such as prolonged audio-visual desynchronization, span much longer durations and primarily manifest in low and mid-frequency temporal patterns. A standard Mamba block scans the sequence step-by-step (stride 1). While this captures all temporal details, it is computationally redu", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
