y, each stage concludes with a downsampling operation that halves the temporal sequence length. This progressive downsampling structure allows the deeper layers of the backbone to possess a larger effective receptive field, enabling them to model longer-range temporal dependencies and capture coarse-grained, multi-scale contextual information essential for detecting sustained forgery patterns. The number of blocks in the Stem and in each Branch stage are configurable hyperparameters, allowing for flexible scaling of the model’s capacity. III-E Theoretical Analysis We provide a theoretical foundation for our design choices from computational complexity, state-space dynamics, and signal processing perspectives. This analysis establishes a priori design principles and testable predictions that are empirically validated in Section IV . III-E 1 Computational Complexity The standard Mamba scan has complexity 𝒪 ​ ( L ⋅ d state ) \\mathcal{O}(L\\cdot d_{\\text{state}}) . Under skip-scanning with stride p p , we partition the sequence into p p groups of length L / p L/p , processed in parallel. While the asymptotic complexity remains 𝒪 ​ ( L ⋅ d state ) \\mathcal{O}(L\\cdot d_{\\text{state}}) , the reduction in sequential dependency depth from L L to L / p L/p trades sequential overhead for parallel width. Prediction (Efficiency): On modern GPUs limited by sequential recurrence latency, stride- p p scanning should yield inference speedups approaching linear scaling with p p (e.g., ∼ 2 × \\sim 2\\times for p = 2 p=2 ). III-E 2 Unified Sequence as Phase Preserver From a signal processing perspective, cross-modal forgery detection requires modeling phase relationships (e.g., audio-visual synchronization) between modalities. Channel-wise fusion 𝐱 t = [ 𝐯 t ; 𝐚 t ] \\mathbf{x}_{t}=[\\mathbf{v}_{t};\\mathbf{a}_{t}] forces rigid temporal alignment, structurally constraining correlation modeling to local windows | Δ ​ t | ≤ R |\\Delta t|\\leq R (where R R is the effective receptive field). Thus, long-range desynchronization ( Δ ​ t > R \\Delta t>R ) becomes theoretically undetectable. In contrast, our unified sequence [ 𝐕 1 , … , 𝐕 T , 𝐀 1 , … , 𝐀 T ] [\\mathbf{V}_{1},\\ldots,\\mathbf{V}_{T},\\mathbf{A}_{1},\\ldots,\\mathbf{A}_{T}] converts cross-modal correlation into a long-range dependency problem . The SSM can model correlations between 𝐯 t \\mathbf{v}_{t} and 𝐚 t + k \\mathbf{a}_{t+k} for arbitrary temporal lags k k within a single forward pass. Prediction (Phase Modeling): The unified representation should exhibit superior capability in detecting asynchronous forgeries with large temporal offsets compared to channel-wise baselines, which are structurally bound by local alignment constraints. III-E 3 Skip-Scanning: Frequency-Aware Regularization Mechanism Clarification. Skip-scanning via Group-Scan-Merge is architecturally distinct from pooling or downsampling: it retains representations for all tokens while modifying the scanning topology. We analyze this as structured regularization affecting the model’s learned inductive bias. State-Space Perspective. Under stride- p p scanning, the recurrence within each group operates with effective state transition matrix 𝐀 ¯ skip = 𝐀 ¯ p \\bar{\\mathbf{A}}_{\\text{skip}}=\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}^{p} . Since 𝐀 ¯ = exp ⁡ ( Δ ​ 𝐀 ) \\bar{\\mathbf{A}}=\\exp(\\Delta\\mathbf{A}) is typically contractive (i.e., ‖ 𝐀 ¯ ‖ < 1 \\|\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}\\|<1 for well-trained SSMs), we have ‖ 𝐀 ¯ p ‖ = ‖ 𝐀 ¯ ‖ p \\|\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}^{p}\\|=\\|\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}\\|^{p} , which decays exponentially with p p . For instance, if ‖ 𝐀 ¯ ‖ = 0.8 \\|\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}\\|=0.8 , then stride-2 yields ‖ 𝐀 ¯ 2 ‖ = 0.64 \\|\\bar{\\mathbf{A}}^{2}\\|=0.64 (20% reduction) and stride-4 yields 0.41 0.41 (49% reduction). This exponential scaling implies that skip-scanning accelerates the decay of high-frequency state dynamics , biasing the model to down-weight short-term temporal jitter. Frequency-Domain Analysis & Optimal Stride Selection. The effective temporal sampling rate within each group is reduced by factor p p , yielding an approximate effective Nyquist frequency f N eff ​ ( p ) ≈ 1 / ( 2 ​ p ) f_{N}^{\\text{eff}}(p)\\approx 1/(2p) (normalized). Crucially, this is a functional approximation rather than physical downsampling, as our Group-Scan-Merge mechanism retains all tokens via parallel processing. The Nyquist-like constraint emerges specifically from the reduced recurrence depth within each group, which effectively limits the upper bound of temporal frequencies that can be captured during the scanning process. Based on this spectral property, we consider the hypothesis that discriminative forgery patterns—such as semantic-level inconsistencies, prosodic mismatches, and audio-visual synchronization drift—are inherently low/mid-frequency temporal phenomena. This hypothesis is biologically motivated by human perception, where the detection of semantic discontinuities and synchronization errors typically operates at timescales of 50–200ms. In the context of feature sequences extracted at 6.25Hz (our AV-Deepfake1M setting), these physical timescales map to normalized frequencies of approximately 0.05–0.2. Consequently, we posit that the critical discriminative band satisfies f d ≲ 0.2 f_{d}\\lesssim 0.2 . Under this hypothesis, we can theoretically rank stride choices: • Stride 2 ( f N eff ≈ 0.25 f_{N}^{\\text{eff}}\\approx 0.25 ): Optimal. The discriminative bandwidth ( f d ≲ 0.2 f_{d}\\lesssim 0.2 ) is fully preserved with a safety margin, while higher-frequency noise is naturally attenuated. • Stride 4 ( f N eff ≈ 0.125 f_{N}^{\\text{eff}}\\approx 0.125 ): Aggressive. It risks attenuating discriminative cues if f d f_{d} approaches or exceeds 0.125 0.125 , potentially causing information loss. Prediction (Frequency Selectivity): If our hypothesis holds, then: 1. Removing low/mid-frequency components ( f < f d f<f_{d} ) should cause severe performance degradation across all models. 2. Removing high-frequency components ( f > f N eff f>f_{N}^{\\text{eff}} ) should have a minimal or even positive impact on stride- p p models, as these frequencies are already down-weighted by the architecture. 3. Stride-4 should exhibit increased sensitivity to mid-frequency removal compared to stride-2, as f N eff ​ ( 4 ) < f d f_{N}^{\\text{eff}}(4)<f_{d} . Prediction (Robustness): Models with larger strides ( p > 1 p>1 ) possess a low-pass inductive bias. They should exhibit superior robustness to data perturbations that primarily corrupt high-frequency details (e.g., compression artifacts, additive noise, blur) compared to the dense-scanning baseline. Soft Regularization Paradigm. Critically, our mechanism differs from conventional hard-filtering. Rather than discarding high-frequency components at the input level, skip-scanning implements a form of soft structural regularization . By altering the scanning topology, we introduce an inductive bias that accelerates the decay of state dynamics, as mathematically derived in the Supplementary Material. This effectively biases the learning process toward robust, low-frequency temporal patterns. Importantly, the Group-Scan-Merge architecture retains the full representational capacity to encode fine-grained details via all-token retention. This design enables the model to prioritize stable semantic features for detection while adaptively attending to high-frequency cues only when explicitly required by the loss function, such as for precise boundary refinement. IV Experimental IV-A Datasets We conduct extensive experiments on two challenging datasets, covering a wide spectrum of forgery scenarios. • LAV-DF [ 8 ] : A large-scale multimodal forgery dataset comprising 136,304 videos. It features four data types: pristine, visual-only tampering, audio-only tampering, and audio-visual tampering. The forged segments are typically short, with durations ranging from 0 to 1.6 seconds. • AV-Deepfake1M [ 7 ] : The largest multimodal forgery dataset. To ensure the validity of audio-visual temporal localization, we excluded silent videos, resulting in a refined training set of 1,091,420 videos and a validation set of 56,907 videos. We use the validation set for testing as the official test set metadata is withheld. IV-B Implementation Details Feature Extraction. Following previous works [ 34 ] , we utilize pre-extracted features to ensure a fair comparison. For the LAV-DF [ 8 ] dataset, we use the two-stream TSN network pretrained on ActivityNet [", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
